                    <comment id="13009820" author="jonm" created="Tue, 22 Mar 2011 20:16:11 +0000"  >I believe the correct fix for this problem is one of:&lt;br/&gt;
(a) document the proper workaround for the client to avoid the connection leak (perhaps using HttpUriRequest#abort)&lt;br/&gt;
(b) have the caching module consume the response body if present before throwing the exception&lt;br/&gt;
(c) don&amp;#39;t throw an exception here and just treat the noncompliant response as cache-invalidating and uncacheable.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
I think my personal preference is (c) and will start working on a patch to that effect.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
                    <comment id="13009836" author="jonm" created="Tue, 22 Mar 2011 20:59:18 +0000"  >The attached patch implements option (c) above. I&amp;#39;ll commit it tomorrow if there aren&amp;#39;t any objections to this approach.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
                    <comment id="13010122" author="jonm" created="Wed, 23 Mar 2011 13:44:45 +0000"  >Ok, after sleeping on it, I think the fix warrants a little deeper analysis than the patch I posted. For example, if the origin response is a 401 missing the WWW-Authenticate header, this is strictly non-compliant, but shouldn&amp;#39;t affect the caching module, and a client not using the caching module would have to deal with this anyway; so this compliance test ought to be removed. I&amp;#39;ll check the other ones -- there are only about 4 unit tests and associated code.</comment>
                    <comment id="13010162" author="olegk" created="Wed, 23 Mar 2011 15:00:45 +0000"  >Option C sounds good enough to me.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Please do not forget to merge changes you would like included in the 4.1.2 release (if it ever happens) to 4.1.x branch.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Oleg </comment>
                    <comment id="13010164" author="jonm" created="Wed, 23 Mar 2011 15:05:01 +0000"  >@Oleg: will do on the branch merge.&lt;br/&gt;
</comment>
